title: Dual E3D-V6 hot end mount for Solidoodle Workbench or Apprentice

description.text:
This mount is for the solidoodle workbench, but it may work with other setups too. I drew it to try to keep as much of the existing hardware as possible. It is a work in progress, but there are a lot of people waiting for something to get them started. I'll post more info, and an instructional video when I finish getting everything installed. I still need to work on a fan mount. If anyone has any ideas, they are welcome and appreciated. Thanks! Edit: you can follow the progress of this thing in the forum at http://www.soliforum.com/topic/10064/e3d-v6/page/4/ 5/5/15 Just a note. this setup maintains the 31.5mm spacing between the nozzles, but you lose z-height. I need to draw a spacer to make up the height for those who require it. 5/7/15 Added riser pad. Requires 4-m3x12 socket head cap screws. Brings build height to 301mm. Added v2 of mount. Slotted outer screw holes and opened up center for a bit of adjustability. There should be enough for about 2mm either way. Peek fans can be swapped with e3d fans. That makes it possible to mount the existing idler arm with an m3x30 socket head cap screw. Final testing this weekend, but it's almost assembled, and everything fits. I'll post pics of final assembly when it's done. 5/11/15 Updated riser to fit better. Added photos with fully installed setup for reference. video of it working. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HeAxYT4VRls&feature=youtu.be Update 2/17/17
Firmware is in the thing files.

Print dual_e3d-v6_workbench or dual_e3d-v6_workbench_v2 at 100% infill using ABS, PLA, or HIPS. IT doesn't get hot enough up there to make a difference. I didn't need it, but v2 is for folks with hotends that are very different in length. Print the cap the same way. Use existing hardware to install. Update 2/17/17
Firmware is in the thing files. Print riser at 25% or lower if you want out of anything hard. I used M3x20 with washers because the Solidoodle carriage is garbage, and the holes were stretched and worn from overtightening. Don't forget to change your settings to match these: define TEMP_SENSOR_0 5 since the E3D uses a different thermistor
define TEMP_SENSOR_1 5 since the E3D uses a different thermistor define HEATER_0_MAXTEMP 310 since you can get to higher temperatures
define HEATER_1_MAXTEMP 310 since you can get to higher temperatures You can find the firmware at the link below. http://www.soliforum.com/topic/15542/firmware-repository/ Be sure to use their arduino version rather than yours if you have one. Its a standalone executable, so it won't interfere with your existing setup. I set my z offset at 4.55, but it needs adjustment. not bad for a first print though. Enjoy!

title: Flashforge Creator Pro Filament Alignment Bracket

description.text:
Unlike similar designs this alignment bracket was designed to print without support or raft. You will know you need it the first time it happens to you. Let Makersome help before it’s to late. You will be kickin yourself when the filament jumps the spool and wraps around the holder, not allowing it to feed properly, having your extruder head moving around and nothing coming out. With this easy to print project you can have trouble free prints. Instructions:

  • Download the STL file for the Filament Alignment Bracket

  • Pop it into your slicer of choice

  • We recommend using PLA with extruder setting of 200°C

  • If you do not have a Glass Bed Upgrade Kit then we recommend not to use a heated bed, but if you do have the Glass Bed Upgrade Kit then we recommend using a bed temp of 70°C

  • You do not need to use rafting or supports while printing this project

  • Load your project onto an SD card or connect your computer to your printer (just use your preferred method here)
    • Congratulations, you're ready to print! For more fun 3D Printing Projects check out Makersomes Project page http://makersome.com/3d-printing-projects/

description.text:
I recently received my S6 and decided instead of buying a case I would design my own. I also just received a spool of Sainsmart TPU filament and it's nice and flexible and not too pricey. It's perfect for a phone case and I believe it's what some manufacturers use to make some of them.   
I printed multiple sections and made adjustments before printing the entire thing to make sure I was getting all the holes and buttons correct. The material is quite stringie, but layer bonding is the best I've ever seen.   
Add your own design to the back if you want. Later I will be uploading another along with this original.

My print settings using my E3D hotend were:
  • 250C Hotend
  • 60C Bed
  • 25-45 mm/s perimeters
  • Cooling fan doesn't really seem to have a huge effect on it
  • 0.1, 0.2mm layer height (I don't recommend 0.3mm)
  • Sliced with Kisslicer (used support material @61deg w/ 0.5mm gap)
    • Notes:
  • If you print to close to the bed on the first layer or too fast the material can get bunched up in the extruder.
  • Supports can be difficult to remove which is why I specify the high support angle. For me, the material had no problem up to that angle. Aside from the holes and horizontal overhangs, the only other things that should have support are the buttons for the volume/power. I didn't try much bridging, but if you have success with it please share your results.
  • Watch the thin walls around the buttons on your slicer program. Slic3r looked like it cut out parts of them and wouldn't let me set a distance for supports. I didn't try any other slicers.
A gift for a love

This object is special-purpose, it's a replacement for a specific part I lost and has no other usefulness!
It replaces the inside half of the 2-piece floorplate used in the 15-22 .22LR magazine (for the S&W 15-22).  This smaller part is the more likely one to go flying out under spring tension if the magazine is disassembled.  Ask me how I know!

• Print this object.
  • Test fit into the bottom of the magazine, trim off any excess if required.
  • Drill a small hole in the bottom where the circular "dent" is, and screw in a small screw. That screw will serve as the little detent (aka bump) that fits into the hole in the exterior floorplate.
    • This might sound funny to you if you don't own a 15-22 magazine. But trust me, if you're here to print out a replacement you'll know exactly what I'm talking about.

title: New Chess Piece is a Game Changer - Introducing the 'Earl'

description.text:
This 'new' chess piece adds another dimension to the traditional game that is popular all over he world. The pieces in the modern game of chess depict royalty and the church. For this reason I've named the new piece 'Earl' but it could just as easily be called Baron or Lord, all of which are regarded as  being a Noble in the medieval hierarchy.  However, 'Earl' seemed the best to me as an Earl is not too senior and this piece replaces two pawns on the front row at the start of the game.   
How to play with the 'Earl':   
As with the Knight/Rook/Bishop each player starts with two Earl's  
The Earl starts the game on the front row and replaces the two  pawns in front of the Bishops  
The Earl is similar to a pawn in that his moves are restricted. However, he can always move up to two squares at a time (a Pawn can only move two straight forward on the first move).   
An Earl can move straight and diagonally including moving sideway and back A pawn cannot do this.  
This makes the 'Earl' a very useful player because he can move in all directions but is limited to two squares at a time.   
An 'Earl' can take on both straight and diagonal moves.   
Unlike pawns, if an Earl' reaches the opposing end of the board it cannot be swapped for one of their previously taken pieces.   
All other rules stay the same. This keeps it easy so players quickly adapt...  
Why play with 'Earls':  
Adds a new dimension to the traditional game. This doesn't necessarily make the  game quicker but gives a player loosing a number of key pieces an increased chance of still claiming victory. This can make it all the more interesting and challenging.   
If one player is significantly better than another, such as when an experienced player is teaching a novice, the experienced player can start with all the traditional pieces and the novice is given Earl's as a competitive advantage. This can help new players stay engaged as, without an advantage, they can get tired or losing all the time.   
Note: If you like this design check out all my other designs...

On a Replicator 2 print at 0.20mm/Std. resolution, 3 shells and 50% fill. Use Raft for ease of removal but no support required.
The .stl is for one Earl only but you obviously need to print two in white and two in black to exchange for the white and black pawns. The design is scaled to be slightly shorter than a Rook/Castle but clearly larger than a pawn so it is easily identified like all other chess pieces. As different chess game manufacturers pieces will vary slightly in size you may want to scale up / down accordingly.

description.text:
I made these glasses since I couldn't work up the nerve to buy real Oakley sunglasses so I figured the next best thing was to buy a pair of replacement lenses and then make a 3D printed frame. They work well and they are a great conversation starter. As an added bonus if you drop them in the ocean they float since they are mostly hollow. The frame has arm spacers and the arms have frame spacers to help with the clearance of the joint during printing. These spacers simply snap off after printing. Tip for others trying to make a frame fit another lens of a different shape.
1.Take a picture of the lens from the front and then the top.
2.Insert this picture into your 3D design software and scale to size.
  • Draw the lens shape from the front then top.
  • Extrude both shapes at 90 degrees from each other accordingly.
  • Use a boolean intersect operation to create a nice lens profile.
  • Scale this by about 1% to create some clearance for use in the frame design.

Frame:
Print at 0.1mm layer height with raft and support. (minor touchups)
Print upside down and try to get the flattest spot you can. I usually rotated it to have the biggest foot print possible. The frame has arm spacers at the the hinge joint. Arms:
The arms have a nice flat bottom to be printed on without supports or raft. The arms have a frame spacer at the end to provide proper clearance in the hinge joint. I found this was the best way to ensure the tolerances stay consistent any require little to no clean up for assembly. Extra Materials:
QTY of 4 Stainless steel #1-64 5/16" long Phillips head machine screws.
QTY of 1 Replacement lenses for Oakely Jawbone from Revant Optics
http://revantoptics.refr.cc/QWS6MP2

description.text: I love Zomboe's Thing9. Separating the design into different prints provides several advantages for me; control over the settings for each part allowing for better overall print quality, ability to try variations on the design without performing a full reprint, increased ease of post processing, and fewer failed prints due to that darn tower falling to pieces near the end. I am also able to print the curve as a hollow tube allowing me to string an LED to the tower turning it into a nightlight.

• Download
  • gcode
  • Print
  • Assemble
    • Settings and tricks I used, as always your mileage may vary. Thing9curve:
    Read this post www.gruelabs.blogspot.com I've got about a clean print bed if you have problems with your print sticking or curling at the base. Mine is stuck solid even with its minimal footprint after a quick clean. Activate Cool and/or use a cooling fan at nozzle. If the air around the nozzle is too hot the current layer of the print will curl up causing the above layer to splutter outside your perimeter giving that ugly droopy look, too cool and the smaller leg won't laminate correctly. If this is a problem you can turn your fan on after the two legs meet or activate multiply and print two at once, this will help each one cool slightly as the other copy is worked on. For a hollow print
    Extra Shells on Base = 0
    Extra Shells sparse layers = 2 (this allows a fully solid surface even on gradual slopes)
    Extra Shells alternate Solid layers = 2
    Infill = 0 (will also help warping do to internal stress as there is no internals)
    In Carve uncheck "Infill in direction of Bridges" Thing9base:
    The base has a side with a gradual slope, high infill or extra shells should improv appearance. Activate Cool and/or fan at nozzle as the top of the wall will thank you for it. Otherwise its a basic print. Thing9tower:
    I turned on Multiply, did two at once and had no problems. Assembly:
    Slide the larger leg through the hole in the tower and snap or glue them into place, pop on the tower and be impressed; be impressed with Zomboe, your machine, and yourself...good job.

title: A better hummingbird feeder ant trap

description.text: This is a proof of concept and practice exercise, to turn my real-world invention into a THING! My first printer is still on the way, so I haven't had a chance to print it yet. Other ant traps I've seen here are basically a cup in one form or another, to hold water. The problem with this is that it can dry out and collect debris. This one is different. It provides a permanent barrier by means of a smelly (to ants) substance that they won't cross. It consists of a shallow tray to hold said substance, with a cover against the rain. What smelly substance, I hear you asking? Talcum powder. Ants hate it. My real-world version, in the picture, consists of an upside down jar lid covered by an upside-down tuna can. It ain't pretty, but it works! It's kept my feeders ant-free for 2 summers. And it's set-it-and-forget-it. One dose of powder works from spring through fall. The thingy version works the same way, with even less muss and fuss. You put a layer of talcum powder in the shallow bottom tray, drop the cover open side down over the hook/post to rest on its support, and hang it up. Well, not so fast -- first you have to drill a hole for a screw-in hook on the bottom, which you will have to get at the hardware store. I wanted to put a hook on the bottom, but I couldn't see how the thing could be printed like that. I strongly suggest putting some caulk around the cover hole after it's in place, to keep water out. Use real talcum. Ants will eat corn starch. I've also read that cinnamon, black pepper, garlic, and mint will work. So if anyone feels adventurous, give it a print and tell me everything that's wrong with it! This is licensed for personal, non-commercial use.

This has been a relatively useful project for me.  This wire rack holds two rows of up to 7" wire spools or 12" spools if you decide to cut out an additional base piece.  It's primarily constructed from 1/4" ABS sheet with 1/2" electrical conduit to hold the spools.  ABS sheet generally comes with one textured side (which you might be able to see in the photos) and one flat side, and it's pretty resilient stuff.  You should also be able to stack these racks and bolt them together, but I haven't built a second one yet to see how well this works.

If you've got an Epilog, here's the settings I used on my 35W Mini18 to cut 1/4" ABS:
Speed: 3%
Power: 55%
Freq: 500Hz The entire frame is held together with 1" L-brackets and 1/2" #8-32 bolts. The handle is just a drawer handle I liked from the hardware store and is held on with 1/2" #8-32 bolts as well. The base is made from 2 ABS sheets, one with the holes to mount it to the frame and one with wells for the screw heads so they don't scratch up whatever you end up setting the rack on. These are held together with ABS cement (which should be available at any hardware/home improvement store). I clamped these pieces together but setting something heavy on the pieces while the cement sets should be sufficient. You'll attach this to the frame with 3/4" #8-32 Bolts (the bolts in the photos are 1" bolts, I didn't have any 3/4" bolts on hand at the time). I used a small pipe cutter to cut 2 16" lengths of 1/2" galvanized electrical conduit, which should leave relatively smooth edges on the pipe. This stuff has an outside diameter of about 3/4", which is about the inside diameter of the 5" spools in the picture. I found that the rack seemed sufficiently sturdy without L-brackets on the outside retaining pieces of the frame, but I'll probably add them later. Here's a list of what you'll need from the hardware store: 36x 1/2" #8-32 Bolts 4x 3/4" #8-32 Bolts 16x 1" L-Brackets 40x #8-32 Nuts 1x ABS Cement 1x Cabinet Handle 2x 16" lengths of 1/2" Metal Electrical Conduit You can also cut a second base (you'll only need the plate with the mounting holes) and bolt it under the handle if you want to use the rack for spools larger than 7". If you decide to do this you'll need to substitute the 4 1/2" #8-32 Bolts holding the handle on for 3/4" ones. Feel free to contact me with questions or if you'd like a set of laser cut parts for this project.

title: HIC Prusa i3 20A 12V Power Supply Cover

description.text:
This my first attempt to cover up the power supply with a plug socket and switch. Got tired of going under the desk to plug/unplug the 3D printer.   
Please feel free to adjust this design.

The cover can be a bit tricky to attach. Once printed solder the plug socket and switch so the wires go through the openings then insert. The switch just pushes in but the socket uses two 3m bolts and nuts. Since I live in the UK I have earthed the power supply. Each wire has a round connector so attaching to the power supply is much easier, safer and has a better connection. Heat shrink was used but insulation tape can be used instead just to cover the any metal showing, e.g. = the connectors. Please make sure you have enough length of wire but not too long. Once the socket and switch are in place feed the red and black wire through the large round hole underneath. again I used two round metal connectors. Before attaching the cover place a 3m nut into the small slot on the end (right side). Make sure the nut has it's flat end pointing up and down. It can be a tight fit but with some help from the small flat screw driver it can be placed correctly making sure it lines up with the hole. Unscrew the bolt on the left side bottom with a cross head screw driver, you may need a bigger type. Now place the cover into place making sure the small ledge is over the metal where the screw came from and the nut lines up with the hole on the right side. Use a 3m bolt (not too long) through the metal hole and make sure the bolt tightens up in the nut (not too tight). The fun part is placing the screw back into the hole. The top hole is large enough for the screw and driver to fit through. You may need to look from the side and guide it to the hole on the cover (that small ledge). Once the screw and bolt is in place plug it in and power up.
Enjoy!

These are simple 100 mm calipers that I designed for a class I am teaching at my local Maker Space (http://www.MakerSpace307.org). The calipers are made using both 3D printing and laser cutting. These calipers are very inexpensive, the total cost per caliper is less than $1.00. Currently they are only capable of outside measurements and only have a millimeter scale. I made the caliper body with inkscape and the amazing "Scale Generator" extension. http://wiki.inkscape.org/wiki/index.php/Extension_repository#Scale_Generator

Materials Needed:
  • 3 mm Acrylic
  • PLA Filament
  • .#6 wood screw
    • Cut the .SVG from the 3mm Acrylic. I used the following settings on our Full Spectrum 45W laser
  • Vector Engrave (RED) 100 Speed 10 Power
  • Vector Cut (BLACK) 10 Speed 100 Power
    • 3D Print the slide, the settings I used were with 0.3 mm layer height and 15% infill. I designed the file for PLA so if you use another material you might have to make an adjustment. Once you have the main body cut and the slide 3D printed you will need to take the #6 screw and install it in the smaller hole in the acrylic. If you screw is sticks through the material just use a pair of pliers and cut the screw and file it so that it is smooth. Alternatively you could use a machine screw and nut to accomplish the same thing.

This was designed to print on a XYZ DaVinci and fills most of the 200mm x 200mm bed.
The gap between the inside pin and the hole in the hinges is designed to allow movement without slop. If you reduce or expand this print the hinges might not work. I've included the other files (including the hinges) for anyone that might want to use them in their own designs.

description.text:
I've been slowly tweaking dissidence's printable Mendel frame, and I think I'm not far from something useable. I started thinking about what's next, and thought a rail and wheel might work for the Y axis, so I made this! Its supposed to be an upsidedown T rail with tab&slot to chain the pieces to make longer rails, and three wheel pieces that go together to sit firmly on the rail. 
Yeah, its not so pretty. When you print 3 small wheels like this, the stringing between them is so bad that when you trim them, they become square. The smallest doesn't even have a hole thru the middle.
The rail looks OK, but the tab&slot doesn't work. I'm going to try making it wider. Also, for this to work well, your printer will need to be better calibrated than mine. The rail has a bit too much plastic extruded at the ends, which would make the wheels, if they worked, tend to stick at the interfaces. Another thing to do is print the part on a diagonal to get the most length possible out of the platform.

This is designed to sense whether or not my garage door is open.  Since the door doesn't always stop at the same place when rolled up a magnetic sensor wouldn't work.  
The friction between the sensor arm and the plastic pin causes by the microswitch roller sometimes keeps the arm from falling back down so I added a nut for weight that is held on by a small screw.  This version includes a hole in the sensor arm for the screw.

You might need to clean up the hole through the sensor arm with a drill bit (depends on your printer).  I printed with thick shells to allow for this.  
Apply a little acetone to just the smallest diameter portion of the pin and insert through the arm into the plate.  Try to avoid getting any acetone on the arm.  You can work the arm back and forth as the  acetone dries to make sure the arm doesn't stick.

I have a Catrike Expedition (Three wheeled bicycle).  The 'seat stays' on it are at a different angle to normal bicycles and taillights designed to mount on normal bicycle seat stays or seat posts end up pointing up in the air.

description.text:
Plants like water. But watering plants needs to be done in the correct way. If you give a plant water each day, the roots will not grow deep into the ground and the plant will become 'lazy': this way it will suffer a lot from a short period without rain.
The best way is to give the plant a lot of water, so this sink deep into the ground: now the plant will grow deep roots, making it stronger. The best way to give water, is to give the plant a lot of water, let this sink in and then give some more water. For plants having a small access point to water, this makes it difficult, since the small area can only take up the water slowly. So you should be able to give the plant a small stream of water, but for an extended period. And here is the solution. 'Slow water' allows you to screw a bottle on top and this will then deliver the water in a small stream until the bottle is empty. The whole model is provided, as well as seperate models for printing in 2 colors.

Screw a bottle on top, cut the bottom out and fill with water.  
There is a hole (was not open when I printed it) in the base. You can either make a very small hole to get a stream of water, or else open the big hole, put duct tape around it and pierce this with a needle.

description.text: You can buy linear actuators off the shelf, but none that allow for accurate displacement measurement AND high load rating for this price. The finished model shown can push or pull up to 300 lbs and it moves at about 0.5 in/min. I used it on a special project but you can use it for whatever you want! This assembly is a component of the Testrbot open source universal test machine: http://www.instructables.com/id/TestrBot-The-300-Universal-Test-Machine/ I've also provided 'Base Type 2' files if you want to make a higher speed configuration. (In this config you wouldn't need the gears, as seen in photo 3.)

For complete Excel bill of materials see 'Actuator' section of TestrBot BOM here:
https://cdn.instructables.com/ORIG/F7U/ROLA/J1CEY4G5/F7UROLAJ1CEY4G5.xlsx I picked a stroke of 5.375”, but the actuator can have any stroke you want. I have provided the equations below for determining the actuator component lengths for a given stroke, in case someone wants to use this design for something else. Stroke = You pick! Small PVC pipe length = stroke + 3.125” Large PVC pipe length = stroke + 1.625” Anti-Rotation Rod length = stroke + 2.625” Threaded Rod length = stroke + 4”
